<BlogPost {...meta}>
  <p>There's a number every loan officer should have tattooed somewhere: it takes <strong>five or more follow-up contacts</strong> to convert a typical lead — and <strong>44% of agents stop after one</strong>. I wrote about that gap in <a href="/blog/the-follow-up-gap">The Follow-Up Gap</a>. This piece is the other half: the actual cadence that gets you to touch five without it eating your week or feeling like pestering.</p>

  <p>Because here's the thing nobody admits. The reason most people stop at one isn't laziness. It's that they don't have a <em>system</em> — so every follow-up becomes a fresh decision: <em>Should I reach out? What do I even say? Is this annoying?</em> Multiply that friction across forty leads and of course you quit. A cadence removes the decision. You're not deciding whether to follow up; you're just running the play.</p>

  <h2>Why a cadence beats willpower</h2>

  <p>The leads that need five touches are, almost by definition, the ones who aren't ready today. They're saving a down payment, waiting on a lease, repairing credit, talking to a spouse. None of that resolves on your timeline. So if your follow-up depends on you <em>remembering</em> and <em>feeling motivated</em> on the right random day eight weeks from now, it won't happen.</p>

  <p>A cadence flips that. You decide once — up front — what the sequence looks like, and then you just execute the next step when it comes due. The discipline moves from "remember to follow up" (hard) to "do the thing on today's list" (easy).</p>

  <p>One rule before the cadence itself: <strong>every touch has to carry value.</strong> "Just checking in" is the fastest way to train someone to ignore you. Each contact should give them something — a number, an answer, a next step — so that hearing from you feels useful, not needy.</p>

  <h2>The 5-touch cadence</h2>

  <p>Here's the sequence I've run for years. Treat the timing as a default, not a law — the right pace depends on the buyer's actual timeline. But this is the skeleton.</p>

  <h3>Touch 1 — Within the hour: set the relationship, not the sale</h3>
  <p>Speed is the whole game on the first touch. Reach out the same day the referral comes in — within the hour if you can. Don't pitch. Introduce yourself, confirm you've got their info, and give one easy next step.</p>
  <blockquote>"Hi Sarah — Will connected us about your home search. No rush on anything; I just wanted to put a face to the name and make sure you have my number. When you're ready to talk numbers, I can put together a quick payment scenario so you know exactly where you stand. Either way, I'm here."</blockquote>
  <p>Notice what that does: it lowers the pressure, names the referring agent (borrowed trust), and plants a concrete, valuable next step they can say yes to whenever they're ready.</p>

  <h3>Touch 2 — Day 2–3: deliver something useful</h3>
  <p>This is where most people send "just following up" and lose. Instead, deliver value tied to what you learned on the first call. A payment scenario. A pre-approval breakdown. A one-line answer to the question they actually asked.</p>
  <blockquote>"Quick one, Sarah — I ran the numbers on the $625K range you mentioned. With 5% down on a 30-year, you're looking at roughly $X/month all-in. Happy to adjust for a different price or down payment whenever. Want me to send the full breakdown?"</blockquote>

  <h3>Touch 3 — Week 1: address the specific blocker</h3>
  <p>Every not-ready buyer has a reason they're not ready. Your third touch should speak directly to <em>theirs</em> — the DTI worry, the down-payment gap, the credit question, the lease that ends in September. Generic follow-ups feel like spam. A message about <em>their</em> exact obstacle feels like help.</p>
  <blockquote>"Sarah — you mentioned the car loan was eating into your budget. I mapped out what your numbers look like the month after that's paid off — it actually opens up about $40K in buying power. Want me to walk you through it?"</blockquote>

  <h3>Touch 4 — Week 2–3: switch the channel, keep it human</h3>
  <p>If your first three touches were email, your fourth should be a text (or a quick voicemail). Switching channels gets you out of the inbox graveyard, and a short, human message reads completely differently than a fourth email.</p>
  <blockquote>"Hey Sarah, it's Jay — no agenda, just thinking about your search. Still aiming for after the lease ends? I'll keep an eye on rates for you in the meantime."</blockquote>

  <h3>Touch 5 — ~Day 30: value plus an exit ramp</h3>
  <p>By the fifth touch, you either have a responsive lead or a quiet one. Either way, give value <em>and</em> an explicit exit ramp. Counterintuitively, offering an easy out gets more replies — people respond to "no pressure" because it's a relief.</p>
  <blockquote>"Sarah — I don't want to crowd your inbox, so I'll back off the regular check-ins. If the timing's just not right yet, totally fine — say the word and I'll circle back later this year. And if anything changes, I'm one text away."</blockquote>

  <h2>What happens after touch five</h2>

  <p>If they're still quiet, you don't drop them — you <strong>downshift to long-term nurture.</strong> That means a low-touch, value-first rhythm: a monthly rate or market note, a check-in tied to their trigger date (lease end, bonus, school year), nothing salesy. The goal is simply to still be standing there, useful, when their "not yet" finally becomes "now."</p>

  <p>This matters because of another number from <a href="/blog/the-follow-up-gap">the last piece</a>: 70% of buyers interview only one agent. Whoever's still in front of them when they're ready usually wins by default. Long-term nurture is how you make sure that's you — not the lender who happened to email the week they got serious.</p>

  <h2>The honest problem with all of this</h2>

  <p>Everything above is simple. It is not easy — because the system <em>is</em> the hard part. Knowing the cadence does nothing if you can't track forty leads at five different stages across email and text, each on their own timeline, while you're also closing the deals that are actually moving. That's exactly the point where "I'll follow up" quietly becomes "I forgot," and the lead slips into the gap.</p>

  <p>That's the part we built <strong>DealSync</strong> to carry. Every lead sits on a shared deal card with its next follow-up date and the <em>reason</em> it's where it is. Each morning, a digest tells you exactly who's due today — no hunting, no remembering. And when you open one, the AI Coach reads your notes and the engagement and <strong>drafts the next message for you</strong> — the right touch, in the right tone, at the right step. Copy, tweak, send. Touch three becomes thirty seconds instead of a blank page you avoid.</p>

  <p>The cadence is the strategy. A system that makes the cadence happen on time, without willpower, is what actually converts the lead. You bring the relationships. Let the software make sure none of them go quiet on your watch.</p>

  <p>— Jay Miller</p>
